    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-04-14T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-04-14T09:00:00-05:00" n="420"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d420">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">683.84A/4–1452: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 420<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Syria (<persName corresp="#p_CC1" type="from"
                            >Cannon</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d420fn1">Repeated to Tel Aviv, London, and Paris.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Damascus</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-04-14T16:00:00+02:00"
                            >April 14, 1952—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>585. Department pass Defense. Thanks Major <persName corresp="#p_JLC1"
                        >Jaddid</persName>’s cooperation attitude <gloss target="#t_MAC1"
                        >MAC</gloss> chairman Col. <persName corresp="#p_TCS1">Taxis</persName>
                    obtained Syrian consent in January Israel closing Jordan River sluice gates in
                    order repair Daughter <persName corresp="#p_JJK1">Jacob</persName>’s Bridge
                        (<gloss target="#t_Legtel1">Legtel</gloss> 462, February 6). Israeli have
                    made little effort repair bridge, but have taken advantage opportunity work
                    intensively on drainage project when weather permitted.</p>
                <p>Now that water level receding Syrians state floodgates must be opened permit
                    continued irrigation valuable crops Bouteiha farm and last week asked <persName
                        corresp="#p_TCS1">Taxis</persName> relay request. Israeli refused, stating
                    Syrians had no say on affairs in zone which is “under Israel sovereignty”.
                    Syrians aroused by Israel intransigence and there were some mutterings they
                    would take action open floodgates if <persName corresp="#p_TCS1"
                        >Taxis</persName> unable do so.</p>
                <p>In emergency meeting with Israel chairman April 12 we understand <persName
                        corresp="#p_TCS1">Taxis</persName> succeeded in obtaining his agreement open
                    gates provided <persName corresp="#p_TCS1">Taxis</persName> would seek consent
                    Syrians allow closing gates few hours daily for short period permit completion
                    repairs bridge. While <persName corresp="#p_JLC1">Jaddid</persName> and owners
                    Bouteiha farm probably would agree <pb facs="0955" n="915" xml:id="pg_915"/>
                    such arrangement, they are convinced Israeli using bridge repairs only as
                    pretext pursue drainage project. Situation thus continues potentially dangerous
                    and military attaché and Legation officer planning early visit zone observe
                    developments.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Comment:</hi> Most unsettling factor continues be Israeli
                    reiteration claim of sovereignty over zone and denial Syrian demands discuss in
                        <gloss target="#t_MAC1">MAC</gloss> affairs within zone affecting Arabs
                    including drainage project which also affects property owners in Syria (<gloss
                        target="#t_Legtel1">Legtel</gloss> 319, December 4 [<hi rend="italic"
                        >3</hi>]<note n="2" xml:id="d420fn2">For text, see <ref
                            target="frus1951v05#pg_130">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1951, vol. V, p.
                        1309</ref>.</note>). Israel continued non-compliance important provisions
                    May 18, 1951 <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> resolution is factor striking
                    root Syrian confidence in <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> and west which in
                    other fields has been improving.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cannon</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
